step.context:
\text{If Q is the quantity sold, R is rate per item} \\
\text{and A the amount raised, the relationship} \\
\text{between Q, R and A is}

\text{If the quantity matrix Q looks like this} \\
\overbrace{
Q=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
  25 & 12 & 34 \\
  22 & 15 & 28  \\
  26 & 18 & 36
\end{array}\right] }^\text{paper bag | scrap-book | pastel sheet}
\begin{array}{c}
  \small\text{School A} \\
  \small\text{School B} \\
  \small\text{School C}
\end{array} \\
\text{what does the rate matrix R look like so that} \\
Q\times R = A\text{ (amount matrix)}?

step.reason:
\text{Each item in a row of the quantity matrix } \\ \text{multiplies with the appropriate rate from } \\ \text{rate matrix. When added together, these } \\ \text{products represent the total amount } \\ \text{raised by a school. Therefore,} \\
\left[\begin{array}{ccc} 25 & 12 & 34 \\ 22 & 15 & 28 \\ 26 & 18 & 36 \end{array}\right]\times \left[\begin{array}{c} 20 \\ 15 \\ 5 \end{array}\right]=\left[A_1 \quad A_2\quad A_3\right], \\ \text{where,} \\ A_1=(25\times 20+12\times 15+34\times 5)=850 \\ A_2=(22\times 20+15\times 15+28\times 5)=805 \\ A_3=(26\times 20+18\times 15+36\times 5)=970 \\
\text{Such an exercise certainly inculcate feelings} \\ \text{of kindness, togetherness with the community}\\ \text{and a sense of what teamwork can achieve.}
